Dr Eric Goemare (R), and Nompumelelo Mantangana, a doctor and nurse with Doctors Without Borders (MSF), look at the progress being made in setting up a field hospital being set up in a sports hall in Khayelitsha, near Cape Town, on May 22, 2020. CAPE TOWN - The Western Cape government said it may have a shortage of 1,600 beds for COVID-19 patients. Western Cape Premier Alan Winde described in a statement that the province's modelling data has been updated with the latest available information and recalibrated their projections accordingly. READ: Western Cape COVID-19 infections to peak by July: Winde "We have taken significant steps to make sure we are prepared for the peak based on the best available evidence and modelling, but it is difficult to know exactly how pronounced the peak will be at this stage," he said. That being said, the statement indicated a peak in the province would be expected from late June to early July. READ: COVID-19: Mkhize calls for a focus on Western Cape Initially, projections indicated that 6,200 beds would be needed. It is now projected to be 7,800. Deaths are expected to reach over 9,000. READ: Western Cape puts plan in place to curb spread of COVID-19 "My cabinet will now meet to consider these new projections, and together with the National Government, including the National Treasury, we will consider both whether and then when and how, to bring online additional bed capacity," Winde said. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.